@NODE COTS_Charity "CDOpus - Children of the Storm"
@{par}
@{par}                             @{fg shine}Children of the Storm@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}@{u}                                                                               @{uu}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE@{ub}: This information hasn't been updated for a long time, but the ideas are
still the same - only more things have been accomplished since it was written.
The address at the end IS still correct.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}Contacting COTS via the Internet:
@{par}@{fg fill}EMail: @{fg text}Athy Demetriades <athy@cotstorm.demon.co.uk>
@{par}  @{fg fill}WWW: @{fg text}http://www.rmplc.co.uk/eduweb/sites/hampscit/storm.html
@{par}@{u}                                                                               @{uu}
@{par}
@{par}I know that most you out there won't pay anything at all, but I am doing this
in the hope that at least a few people donate even a small amount of money,
because every little penny can be put to some good!
@{par}
@{par}Please, at least read about the charity, Children of the Storm. I not going to
say that anyone who doesn't send off some money should feel really guilty, just
that anyone who does send off some money should feel really great, knowing that
they've helped someone out.
@{par}
@{par}Even if you don't want to send any money (for whatever reasons), you could
always send a letter of support, or spread the word to other people.
@{par}
@{par}I have never asked for any money for all the work I put into these utils,
and I do not gain anything from your donations except knowing that I have helped
some people out. I know that my work is used by a lot of people and that because
of that, I have helped them out in one way or another, so why not help someone
else now! You do have hearts, don't you? Make it worth my while typing all of
this info!
@{par}
@{par}
@{par}                      @{fg shine}Who are the CHILDREN OF THE STORM?@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}In Britain this year, over a hundred young children will be accepted into the
country by the Home Office, seeking political asylum. They may be just eleven
or twelve years old. Often they have travelled across continents alone. They
may have just lost their parents, seen brothers and sisters brutally murdered,
or suffered beatings or torture themselves. Whilst our Government offers them
basic shelter and the long-term possibility of war-refugee status in the UK,
they can live here for weeks and months under the threat of instand
deportation, sometimes forced to live rough without provision for food,
clothing and other simple necessities. Far from their home and their culture,
hungry, fearful and insecure, these children attempt, often with an astounding
dignity and human spirit, to survive and grow despite the weight of unbearable
memories they carry deep within...
@{par}
@{par}                                  @{fg shine}Background@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}Since 1989 several members of the staff at Hampstead School have been building
up a support network for refugee children attending the school who have little
or no family back-up, few resources, and are often in a critical emotional
state.
@{par}
@{par}Achievements to date include:
@{par}
@{par}· Providing food, shelter and income for regugee children, working with the
@{par}  Tavistock Clinic which is providing counselling services and advising
@{par}  teachers,
@{par}· Forging links with the local authority (London Borough of Camden) to put
@{par}  children and carers in touch with any relevant support agencies,
@{par}· Establishing a social club in which refugee children are offered additional
@{par}  tuition and emotional support by their fellow pupils at the school,
@{par}· Acting as the children's advocates in relation to housing, social services,
@{par}  social security etc.
@{par}
@{par}                                    @{fg shine}Status@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}Registered Charity number 1035774
@{par}Consultant: Sheila Kasabova, Refugee Co-ordinator, Camden Council
@{par}Consultant Psychologist: Maureen Fox, Consultant Psychotherapist at the
@{par}                         Tavistock Clinic
@{par}Legal Consultants: Bindmans (services at no charge)
@{par}Accountants: Alan Heywood, Chartered Accountants (services at no charge)
@{par}
@{par}                              @{fg shine}Aims and Objectives@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}1.  To continue to build on the existing project achievements outlined,
@{par}2.  To extend knowledge acquired by staff and pupils of the school to other
@{par}    schools and bodies dealing with refugee children through teacher-training
@{par}    programmes, conferences, booklets etc.
@{par}
@{par}                @{fg shine}Summary of Projects in Progress or Anticipated@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}1.  Publishing a booklet: the Hampstead Story, by those involved in the
@{par}    project, outlining the problems Hampstead School itself has encountered
@{par}    with refugee children and strategies for dealing with them. To be
@{par}    delivered free of charge to every school in the country.
@{par}    Cost: £9,000. Project in progress.
@{par}2.  Expanding the social club outlined above to include students from other
@{par}    local schools including primary schools.
@{par}    Cost: £50 per month. Project in progress.
@{par}3.  Employing a full-time counsellor at Hampstead School to counsel children
@{par}    and train staff in counselling techniques.
@{par}    Cost: £38,000 pa.
@{par}4.  Employing an administrative assistant to manage the charity.
@{par}    Cost: £20,000 pa.
@{par}5.  Holding a national conference on problems faced by refugee children in
@{par}    Britain, and strategies for overcoming them, open to any persons or
@{par}    organisations working with regugee children (teachers, welfare and social
@{par}    servicesm volunteer groups etc.)
@{par}6.  Employing a fundraiser.
@{par}    Cost: £15,000 pa.
@{par}
@{par}                                  @{fg shine}Conclusion@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}The project originated at Hampstead School is the only one of its kind. Due
largely to recent wide coverage and acclaim in local, national and
international media, it is increasingly being recognised by local authorities
as a role model for other schools. Central to the project's success is teacher
Athy Demetriades, who has assisted on training days in schools around the
country. Regular requests for her to speak now come from solicitors,
educational psychologists, welfare services and radio programmes as well as
schools. On average, she fulfils one such engagement per week. She is, in
effect, becoming one of few experts on the all-round care of children suffering
a unique combination of problems - the destruction of the childhood together
with the loss of citizenship and any automatic recourse to law and welfare that
citizenship entails.
@{par}
@{par}Sponsorship for Children of the Storm would ensure that the work originated at
Hampstead School can continue. It would also lay the foundations for a training
programme enabling teachers and carers right across the country to provide the
basics of security and education to refugee children.
@{par}
@{par}                              @{fg shine}Further Information@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}This is basically what you would find on the letter head:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}Children Of The Storm
